content.description: Sit start on the low sidepull jug as for "Everything is Awesome",  pop up and left making the reverse moves of Sigmund Freud to end at the top of "Gimme Back My ID" where you do tricky static moves or full on dyno your way to the top mega-jug.  Exciting little extension!
content.location: Far right corner face of Leggo My Ego boulder

content.description:
A wonderful line that starts with a techy slab traverse and ends with an all out dyno. Classic!

Start sitting on the right side of the Leggo my Ego boulder with a good left hand pinch. Establish on the slopey foot ledge and then traverse left on tenuous underclings and smeary feet until you can reach the rail of Leggo my Ego. Finish with the Leggo my Ego dyno.
content.protection: A few pads. The landing is good.
content.location: Just right of Leggo my Ego.

content.description: Start seated as for Gimmie Back My ID. Work your way right around the arete to a low jug at shin height, and then climb straight up.
content.location: Shares a start with Gimme back my id on the right arete of the boulder. Gimme back my id goes to the left and Sigmund Freud goes to the right.

climbs.name: Leggo What's Left of my Ego

content.description: Begin matched on the jug as for Leggo Arete. Delicately traverse right into the rails of Leggo my Ego and awkwardly dyno to the lip, as per.
content.location: On the Leggo my Ego boulder.

content.description:
Start low matched on a ball shaped jug. Find your feet, move up to another ball shaped jug and then move up to a slopey sidepull rail. Dyno for the lip out left and rock over. Trickier than it looks.

There is also a hand far out left and a small crimpy sidepull up high on the right. I have heard this problem can be done statically but I've only ever seen it done with the dyno so your mileage may vary beta wise.
content.protection: Landing is good but it's a big move to the lip so 2 pads isn't the worst idea just for coverage of a broad landing zone.

content.description: Stand start on the arete left of Leggo My Ego with great holds and marginal feet. The crux is pulling up from the first lip to a slopey hold near the top. Once you've made it there, you have to climb right, following good holds to the top.
content.protection: The landing is flat. One pad should be fine.
content.location: Obviously climbed corner of LME boulder, left of the v7 route. Downclimb off the back.

content.description: Sit start on a left-facing ramp feature. Get standing, then use a coarse pocket to get to a jug up and right.
content.location: A few feet to the right of Leggo My Ego.

content.description:
This long technical traverse starts at the far right corner of the Leggo boulder with a sit start, right hand on a good sidepull/jug and left hand either matching or on a small left nubbin,  move up to obvious left jug above and do most of Sigmund Freud in reverse which leads into the intro moves of Gimme Back My ID - once through that,  take a breath and continue on to tip toe through the delicate moves of Stackin' Leggos to finish out on the top of Leggo My Ego.  A nice enduro test piece to give a more difficult spin to such an excellent boulder!  I think we've grown way outta V-grades, so I call it an SBP "white" (or somewhere between v8+/9) For those rare folks who enjoy the sweet pain of Stackin Leggos but need the next level.  If someone has done this in the past,  don't be shy and lets see the steezy footy.

Link to youtube vid: youtube.com/watch?v=P8KKyCZxF3g

Start matched on the far left side of the obvious sloper rail with more or less non-existent feet. Traverse right by either campusing on the tacky slopers or smearing/heel hooking. This will take you to the mantle on the far right side of the boulder. Top out from here.
content.protection: Landing is fine if not a little angled downwards. A pad or so and you should be fine.
content.location: On the Leggo My Ego boulder around the corner from the problem of the same name. Obvious chalked up slopers.

content.description: Start matched on the head height sloper around the corner from Leggo My Ego. There are some small smeary feet and an obvious sloper/start hold. Move out left to a sloping shelf and mantle or throw a heel up to a good right hand hold. Top out from here.
content.protection: Landing is fine if not a little angled downwards. A pad or so and you should be fine.
content.location: On the Leggo My Ego boulder around the corner from the problem of the same name. Obvious chalked up slopers.
